segments.text: These medics look like John Wayne, Pancho Villa, and Audie Murphy all wrapped up in one.
They're humping ammo for everybody.
They've got bandoliers with ammunition, you know, and you'd have to say, how about getting your medical bag there, boy?
Oh, yeah, yeah, I forgot about that.
Because all of a sudden it was real world for them, and that's the last time you ever heard about their conscientious objectors because those guys know us out of the rifle.
They didn't care one way or the other about his personal feelings.
And neither did they once it got real to them, which is what most people in the United States don't understand.
They haven't been, they've never been afflicted with true fear on a daily basis.
And they just really don't know what it's like.
It's kind of like some woman trying to explain to me what it feels like to have a baby.
Well, she can kind of tell me, I can kind of,
but still there's nothing like being there and get the full benefit of the situation.
And you cannot explain to somebody who hadn't been to Vietnam what Vietnam was really like.
And, in fact, it's so different, even people who went to Vietnam, if you have one Vietnam veteran will talk to another Vietnam veteran, you'd think that there's some common bond there.
And, yeah, there is a little bit,
But probably the first question they're going to ask is not what unit you were with, but when were you there?
Because if you were there in 65 or 66, I'm not saying it was like a vacation, but it was not that much happening.
And it changed.
And it changed, and the intensity changed.
And the nastiness changed and increased.
But if you were there in 68 and 69, which was the really high part, then you have, you might say, an even more common of a bond with certain people.
And if you try to talk to some Air Force guy,
you know, about Vietnam.
You know, hard times to the Air Force guy was when they couldn't get smoke glass windows for their hooch with their refrigerated air conditioning.
You know, where these guys were scrounging, you know, for items like that, smoke glass windows or the little portable air conditioners and stuff like that, or their stereos.
Infantry, yeah, I was scrounging for Claymore mines, grenades,

uh, stuff like that, uh, for just to have around, you know, that was important, you know, for me, and, and, you know, they were the nice, nicer things to have, that was your frosting on the cake, uh, because, uh, they were very effective, and they were, you know, real meaningful for you.
Uh, I'd been in, uh, Vietnam for, I guess, probably, uh, seven or eight months, and, and, uh, I went to, uh,
visit an Air Force friend.
My heavy weapons NCO had a brother who was stationed at Cameron with the Air Force, and we went and visited him while we were trying to get some supplies.
And we visited him.
Well, we slept on a bed, had sheets, had showers with hot water, a real luxury and things that are real important to me right now.
I love flush toilets.
I like hot water and I like clean sheets.
I didn't have that for the most part over there.
Contrast that to what you had as compared to what they had, such as what you slept on, where you had to use the restroom, things like that.
You're talking about the North Vietnamese or the enemy type people?
Your infantry.
Oh, my people?
as opposed to the Air Force type people.

Well, you know, the Air Force people had a cafeteria they went to three times a day, and they had their meals prepared for them, and it didn't have any bugs in it, and it was good, clean, edible food.
My last six months, I had to shop on the economy.
In fact, I had to buy, you know, my food.
I was furnished no food.
My meals were not paid for.
I had to buy all my food while I was in Vietnam, which I did not like.
Our government paid all the salaries and all the munitions used and food for the Australians, the New Zealanders, the Koreans.
Everyone who came that fought on our side, our government paid total expenses for all their people.
American officers have to pay
brawl their food, even in combat situations.
Whether you eat it or not, they take it out of your pay, which I didn't think was too cool.
My last six months, which was when I was on this mobile advisory team, which consisted of five people, you had your team commander, an executive officer, there was two officers, you had a medic,
a heavy weapons NCO and a light weapons NCO, and these were basically your teachers.
You know, you taught this, you taught that officers mainly taught the tactics, and your NCOs taught your, you know, all about the weapons that you were going to use.
So, I might teach a class, say, like we're going to have a class today on an L-shaped ambush, and this is the parts that you're going to use.

the weapons that you'll use and and this is the way you set things up you draw little pictures and show everybody how to do it and There's the trail this is where the guys come in when they get in what they call the kill zone and you usually pop a claymore mine on them and that starts everything everybody starts shooting and whoever Stands around the latest usually wins, you know But
It's kind of funny, a lot of the situation out there, but I was spending about $200 a month for food.
I made $471 a month.
Bobcay or a head of cabbage, I would spend $2 for a head of cabbage.
Rice, I could buy rice.
I could buy rice from the Americans, the CIA or the United States Agency for International Development.
Not that the CIA was there.
But I could buy rice from them.
I'm talking about your long grain, double A, wonderful Uncle Ben's type rice.
Not instant, but just real rice.
I could buy 100 pounds of that for $13.50.
100 is about what it cost me.
Conversely to that situation, those same people were giving rice to all of the Vietnamese nationals there.
They'd just come up and they'd just give them all they wanted.
It was amazing.
And of course, you couldn't give it to an American, but you could give it to a Vietnamese.
Why did they say they couldn't give it to you?
We weren't authorized.
It wasn't a program for Americans.
It was a program for the Vietnamese.
because we were, you know, their little rice paddies were getting blown up and that kind of stuff, so we'd just go ahead and give them completely harvested rice.

And really what we were doing, they were still growing their rice in rice paddies, and we were really just providing all the logistical support for the North Vietnamese because they'd just come in there and take all this bagged rice away from them, you know, and they'd have all this rice stacked up in their little bellages, you know, a little hooch, and those guys would just come in there and take it.
So you weren't really helping anybody in any way other than the enemy, who was trying to get you.
Makes a lot of sense.
Well, when you were out there fighting, did y'all jabber-type prisoners, or they were just on the shot?
Well, one thing I really had a great deal of respect for the North Vietnamese type of military.
To me, they were as good as we were.
The only difference between us and them was they had a lot less firepower at their disposal than did we.
But they were motivated.
I thought they did just a real good job.
The South Vietnamese Army I was less than impressed with.
They didn't do a good job.
The South Vietnamese Army, as well as the government,
It was just corrupt.
All they did, they just took our stuff, sold it, used it, you know, really gave you a real negative feeling toward them.
I don't dislike Vietnamese, you know, on an individual basis, but the mountain yard people over there were kind of like the Indians that we talked about earlier.
Very nice people, honest.
You could leave a $300 camera
like if you just kind of left your camera on a table or something in one of the little hooches, you'd come back a week later and still be there.
It wouldn't even been touched.
Whereas the Vietnamese, there was still anything and everything wasn't tied down, and then some things were tied down.
I didn't like that about them.
I didn't like their attitudes about a lot of things.
Of course, I don't know if I'd been in their situation.
I might have the same feelings.
Because, you know, to me, when you peel it all back, it doesn't really make any difference whether it's a French bomb, American bomb, or North Vietnamese bomb.
When it goes off, the damage is still done.
People are hurt.
Properties are hurt.
Animals are hurt.
And you can say you're sorry.
The only difference between us and everybody else is our answer to everything is...
Well, let's say we kill three of your chickens.
Here's X dollars for those chickens and all the chickens that those chickens would produce and all their little grandchildren for chickens.
And we pay them for so many generations of chickens or hogs or whatever it happened to be.
Probably, as far as fighting type action,
there again down where I was the last six months.
Most of that took place at night.
It was again from 9 o'clock at night to about 3 o'clock in the morning.
We located as a central location at a Vietnamese train center.
We built us a little house out of
just ammo boxes and just anything we could find, you know.
And I stole a lot of things.
I was the biggest thief in Vietnam.
I mean, and I really mean that literally, and I say it with a great deal of pride, but I had my antics.
I'd only steal from Americans.
They were the only people that had anything anyway.
But I could not get any support from my own people because I was under, basically, I was assigned to the Vietnamese Army because I was training them.
my last six months.

And basically one of our little missions was to show them, you know, fill out a form and, you know, 18 different copies and give one to this place and, you know, and you would start requesting all of these, whatever you needed, food ammunition, you know.
But it just doesn't work in a Vietnamese unit because most stuff had already been sold anyway.
So you always had these little breakdowns everywhere.
Yeah, we're trying to teach them how.
How to make an American army out of Vietnamese armies.
Kind of like trying to make a Democrat out of a Republican.
It's useless.
That's right.

And before that, they didn't take the time to loan because they were either stealing what they were supposed to be ordering or they were selling what they'd already ordered and it was just a breakdown.
You had that.
There were lots of black market stuff going on there with Americans and with Vietnamese.
The...
The Vietnamese, you had different groups of people in Vietnam.
You had your ethnic Vietnamese, then you had these Mont Yard people.
And the Mont Yard people, they hated all the Vietnamese, North, South, East, West, Indian, Mayan, they didn't like them, any of them, not one.
They had no use for them.

And the only reason they were on our side was because our government said, okay, boys, you help us out, and when this deal's over, then you're going to get these four provinces, which are like counties,
You're going to get Darlac, Khantung, and I forget the name of the other two provinces, and that's going to be your cut out of the war when we win this deal.
And so that's the only reason why they kind of work together.
So the South Vietnamese had a conflict between their own people and the people that live in their provinces, as well as against the North Vietnamese and the American side.
Right.
I've heard that they not only resented the Americans, they resented all of our allies that already helped them.
Oh yeah.
Well, I hate one, I hate all their cousins and everything too, so I tried.
Made for a good working relationship.
Didn't it though?
My only, the only thing that I had total power over was that if I felt like that I or any of my people was in danger,
and that this Vietnamese officer, if he was in charge of an operation, they had no control over me, and I had no control over them.
But what I could do is say, well, boy, if you want to do that, that's fine.
You just go ahead and do it.
But I tell you what, I ain't going to do that.
And when I left, so did my firepower.
And that's what they needed.
And that's what they needed, and they didn't want to go up.
So basically you had...
effective control over, because all you had to do was threaten to leave.
If you left, so did your firepower, and they couldn't do without.
And by threatening them, that still made them resent you.
Right, and they just, yeah, right, they just, you know, they could, you could tell, you know, well, you sorry sucker, you know, you did it to me again, and, you know.
We've already discussed about, you said that, that North Vietnam,
but they were smart about fighting against you at night.
Well, can you kind of compare them to how, kind of tell me what they would normally do in the jungle, how they fought, like?
You know, little traps and stuff like that?
Yeah.
Well, the whole country over there is just riddled with what they call the punchy pits, which are little holes that were dug in the ground, maybe two or three feet deep.
And what they do is they would,
They would take bamboo sticks and sharpen them real sharp and harden them in a fire.
So they're just like steel.
And then they would cover them with either human or animal feces.
And then they'd plant them in the ground with the pointed side up.
So when you stepped in a hole and fell,
then those sticks would go like up your legs or through your hands or your arms or wherever you happen to land on, you know.

But what that does is you get all the bacteria from the feces of the animals or humans gets into your wound and over there you had a real hot, moist climate which is just a perfect breeding ground for bacteria and so your wounds would get infected and
They played the numbers games like we do.
If you kill somebody, they're just dead.
You stack them up like cordwood and deal with them whenever you can.
However, if you wound somebody, for every person that's wounded, it takes about three people to take care of them.
So if you want to play the numbers game, then it's better to wound somebody because
Every time you lose somebody, it takes that many more people to take care of them, that much more facilities.
To transport them.
Right, all kinds of things.
So, yeah, we didn't take too many prisoners.
We took some prisoners.
Most of the time, you know, you just, they're shooting you, you shoot them until they quit shooting, you know.
And they don't give up.
And so most of the time, you had to kill them.
Every once in a while, you would take a prisoner
Normally, you would just send them back.
You'd call in and have them backed out with a helicopter and take them back to some interrogation camp.
And they would talk to them, see what they knew, and that kind of stuff.
And then they'd put them in a PILWP compound.
What other kind of traps did you use?
Well, they had all kinds of, they were real crafty in doing things.
They had lots of different types of bombs that they would make.

They would, you know, you might, Americans are real bad about going through anywhere they go and I see a stock of bananas, you know, and I go, oh, I'm going to go get a banana, you know, and they go over there and rip a banana off and move that banana stalk and it blows up in your face, you know.
You had things like that.
You had the same thing with pineapples.
You had

lots of different tripwires, which was another thing that made everybody real nervous, is because they would take dud rounds that are artillery shells that didn't explode, and all they'd do is just defuse them and crack them open and get the explosive out of them, and then they would make, you know, like a bomb, and they'd use, like, glass or nails or just other steel fragments, so, and pack that in there, and then if you trip something, you know, then that would blow

you know like on you and they were you know they were detonated with either tripwires or they might use a bind you know for a tripwire you know you didn't know if that bind was really a bind or was it a tripwire you know so you and you have to really be observant when you're over there anything that's just out of place at all really needs to be dealt with a real cautious type basis

You'd go in a lot of these little villages, and when you go into a village, then what you really do is you search everything that you can think of in the village, and then you destroy whatever you find.
It might be munitions, it might be food, it might be medicine, it might be radio parts, or you just don't know what you're going to find.
And they had stuff everywhere.

take like little logs they'd hollow out and they might have like mortar rounds in there or they'd have like false walls in the little hooches or false ceilings or false floors and so you'd really take a real good eyeball on a little building that you'd go into you know you'd look at it real good and you kind of mentally step it off uh outside of it and you go on the inside and find it's a couple steps or a step you know shorter and you know hmm

wonder why it's shorter on the inside is on the outside you know how do you train yourself yeah right you learn all this stuff uh you know if you pay attention if you don't pay attention i'll be around anyway so uh anyway uh they'd hide things they'd bury things like they had little pits for like their animals to you know kind of like where pigs would swap around in mud so they had those you know same little pigs and they had uh
you know, like water buffalo, and they'd kind of roll around in the mud, cool off, that kind of stuff.
You know, they'd bury, like, rifles and stuff underneath that.
And, of course, we had, you can use, like, a mine detector.
All it is is a glorified metal detector.
You know, so you could use, you know, things like that, and you start running those things through water, mud, or it's over an area, and you pick up metal, you know, if something's down there.
You can do the same thing if there's wood or walls, stuff like that, though.
We found people hiding behind walls.

You know, yeah, we had, you know, like this one afternoon, this is kind of, I guess, a bad story, I guess, but we were doing a joint operation with the South Vietnamese unit, and we had had, there's a deal there called Spider Holes, where these guys, you know, dig these little holes and they, you know,

they camouflage it real good and they jump up and they'll shoot at you and they'll try to kill somebody and then they'll cover themselves back up and it's real hard, you know, you can't hardly find them.
And, uh, but you know it's somewhere so, you know, you start really looking and then you can usually find, it's like everything else, once you start doing something then you can get good at it.
And, uh, so we, you know, of course we're rooting out these people and there was this one little group in this one village, you know, and, uh, uh,
You know, they kept shooting at us, you know, and we'd stay out of the way of their bullets and stuff.
And so we told them, the Vietnamese, to come out, you know, or we were going to kill them.
And they needed to come out and just turn themselves, you know, give up.
And they weren't going to be hurt, and they weren't going to be killed.
Of course, they didn't believe us.
And, you know, they start shooting at you again every time you talk.
And I just told them, I said, this is your last chance.
And are you going to come or not?
And they start shooting again.
I just took some grenades and rolled in there.
And, you know, they really do a job.
And anyway, this one particular afternoon, and this lady who was standing out there, she was real upset.
And she had to be the wife.
And I told her, man, you tell them, sucker.
We ain't kidding.
And, you know, get them out of there, because we don't want to kill them.
But, you know, we're going to, though.
So she was talking to them, and she couldn't get them to do anything.
And they told me it was their last chance.
So anyway, they threw them a grenade down there, and they killed them.
But anyway, it was wiped out three generations.
It was this lady's father, her husband, and her son.
She wiped out three generations there in a period of five minutes.
And they were North Vietnamese?
Yeah.
Why was she out?
Well, it's not that they were North Vietnamese.
They were just either Viet Cong, which are like VC sympathizers.
Not everybody in the United States agrees with everybody else over here.
We all have our own differences and our own different beliefs.
And they did too, so you had a lot of BC sympathizers over there.
Let me ask you some more of these questions.
You talked about, you know, you rode there six months as a staff and six months on the line.
Yeah.
How'd you feel about that careerism?
Did you feel like,
being six months there, that some officers, knowing that it was their last six months or their last month, they didn't fight as much, knowing that they'd get to go home in the United States?
No.
Everybody just fought the same?
Yeah, because it's kind of like playing a football game.
If you start letting up, you're going to get hurt.
If you quit paying attention, if you quit hitting hard, it's when you kind of sandbag it a little bit, that's when you get hurt.
And over there, if you let up at all, you're gonna get either somebody killed or you're gonna get killed or something like that.
So you really, you had to be going 100%.
So you felt like everybody got it all they had?
Yeah, I did.
I sit here and the news media over there, not over there but over here,
and everything I've ever seen in the news media.
I've never seen anything positive from American news media about Vietnam.
And it was all a totally negative atmosphere.
I personally didn't find that to be the case.
The stereotype Vietnam veteran is a guy who's a drug addict, can't hold a job, just a total misfit.
I don't even know anybody like that.
I've never seen anybody like that.
I guess there's some out there.
Why would they want to be on drugs when that affects their mind?
They've got to have that mind intact to fight that enemy.
That doesn't make sense to me either.
I agree with you.
I've seen the Vietnam movies, Platoon and several other little Vietnam movies that have come out.
I didn't really find them to be that real.
I thought platoon was real, but they perpetrated that show like all infantry people over there, all your platoon, which is platoon was the unit in Vietnam.
It was either tank platoon or infantry platoon, whereas in World War II, it was army against army.
Well, the Vietnamese unit was a platoon.
It was an army.
You didn't have any major clashes of this battalion against that battalion or anything like that.
It was all just dirty little skirmishes all the time going on.
But the movie platoon was a culmination of every war story I ever heard.
And they perpetrated it like that.
Boy, that's what happened every day.

I thought they did a real negative disservice to the American soldier because in that movie, to me, it perpetrated them as being people who got their kicks by bashing little old ladies' heads in with their rifle butts or stopping little kids or stuff like that or being drug addicts and everybody hyped up or something.
I didn't see any of that.
I guarantee you that if I had people, any of my people,
were on drugs, I killed suckers myself.
Because they could affect your life.
Not could, they would.
And either I was naive, and I don't really think that was the case, but I didn't have any of my people were doing it.
All that drug stuff, most of the drugs that were going on over there were people back in the base camps, which is where the big concentration of people was in the first place.
As I mentioned earlier, I've probably been to a couple hundred different presentations on Vietnam that I show my slides that I was over there with, giving lots of talk.
The Rotary Optimist, Lions Club, Ladies Club, all different kinds of schools and all kinds of stuff.
And I found that most of my World War II type age group of people
You know, their big question was, well, how come did that thing, that war take so long to terminate when all you had was really a piece of ground the size of the state of California?
When they were used to going, you know, 20, 30 miles a day like in Europe or something like that, you know, they were hooking them.
You know, why could you, in effect, never get anything done?
Well,

reason you couldn't because there wasn't any fronts over there there was no front you didn't know where the enemy yeah the front was everywhere you know in fact that was my question when i first got there was where's the front i said you're here it's everywhere you don't know where it's everywhere it's nowhere and uh so which is frustrating for americans because americans are used to

to having a problem and dealing with the problem and then going on and forgetting about it, which was real frustrating to people over there because you would go take this hill this day, and then you would leave there and go over here and do another one, and then six days later you'd go back there and take that same hill again.
Well, I did that last week.
Let's go to a new place.
But they had just moved, you know.
So it was really kind of a real frustrating type of atmosphere over there.
The big thing was that we won all the battles, and we lost the war.
Wasn't it, it was hard because you'd see these Vietnamese people, and you couldn't tell if they were the enemy or if they weren't.
And then during the day, they might be your friends.
But at night, when you shot them, you'd find out those weren't my friends after all.
That's right.
And I had that very thing happen to me.
I had some people who were cleaning our hooches when I first got over there when I was in that administrative capacity.
And a couple weeks later, they got killed as being in a Sapper attack at night, which is carrying bombs and blow things up at night.
And so you did have that.
And it was just common.
And you didn't know who they were.
They didn't wear uniforms.
They all looked alike.
That's right.
Did you, were you ever wounded?
No.
You're unfortunate.
Yeah, I have, you know, I got blown off this roof one night, off two stories, but I didn't break any bones.
And, you know, technically, you know, if you get hurt any way, whether it's sitting on a bar stool and you fall over and break an ankle,
You get, if you're in a combat zone, you get a purple heart bar.
I mean, even if you scratch yourself, you get a purple heart.
Of course, I had lots of little scratches and stuff like that, but I didn't ever, you know, put in any purple hearts.
I wasn't into that.
Did you receive any medals?
Yeah, I got a Bronze Star, but...
and told a lot of other people.
Not even a big deal.
It was more of a thank you, I think, than anything else.
Medals were kind of funny.
I used to write up, when I was with the 2nd and 1st Cav, I used to write up, in effect, awards for medals, usually for senior officers who basically were nowhere near any action.
But there again, I told you that everybody in it was from West Point, and they took care of their own.
I wrote up, I can't tell you how many medal awards, silver stars, bronze stars, for colonels, majors, lieutenant colonels who were not there.
So most of those people that you saw hanging
medals on their chest didn't deserve them.
They're more or less promoting their career just by saying, I was over there, and they take their...

I'm not saying that all people did that, because they did, and there were some real legitimate things, but you'll find that a lot of people that really deserve things never even put in for it, didn't want them, were put in for it, were awarded it, and say, I don't want them.
There was a lot of that.
I don't want any of that.
I don't want nothing about that.
They just did their job.
Yeah, and you had asked people, what are you fighting for?
I said, 365 days.
That's what it's for, 365 days.
And so because I was with MACV my last six months, I got to see a lot more of the political side of the war.
I made lots of trips to Saigon.
and got to see some things.
I asked a lot of questions.
What did you think about that government in Saigon a while ago?
Before you mentioned it was corrupt, can you tell me some instances where you saw this?
Yeah, I can give you a few little examples.
And of course, they can't be corrupt unless they've got something to be corrupt for and about.
And I think you can thank our politicians in this country for helping them in that department.
I'll give you a nice example of that.
I talked to a guy in Saigon who was in charge of dispersing docking fees for the military, for the Department of Navy.
Here we are.
We went over there, built them the best harbors, warehouses, docks.
They had nothing.
We went over and built them the best of everything, the best that could technically be built at that particular time.
built it, paid for it with American taxpayer dollars, brought them all of the munitions, supplies to fight their war, in effect, for them, furnished people, material, everything.
And then when we would pull up a ship up to these docks, then they would charge us docking fees for unloading all this stuff.
And I talked to a guy that paid, he personally paid $550 million dollars
in docking fees in one month.
I'll give you another example.
Most of the supplies were for them to use.
Sure.
It was either directly for them or indirectly through the American, the Australian, New Zealand, or Koreans, everybody else who was over there.
It was all for their direct benefit, but indirectly.
used by somebody else.
Why did we pay that?
Why didn't we say, no, we built these for you and we're helping you?
Well, because there's lots of things that go on in war.
Nowadays, your monotype wars are not wars.
It's just like Vietnam really wasn't a war.
It was a conflict.
Korea wasn't a war.
It was a police action.
I think if we have a nuclear holocaust, it's just going to be a disagreement of opinion.
I don't know if we're
all these definitions come from, but to me a war is where people fight and shoot and get killed and hurt people and things like that.
And war in itself is very simple.
You either kill people, you destroy the enemy, you destroy their supplies, or you destroy their morale.
In effect, you make it not worth the effort.
If you're coming down south to fight, and you're from North Vietnam, you're coming down south, and all of a sudden you find out that
all of your homeland just been blown away.
Is this really worth it?
But see, our government chose not to do that.
We could have made it.
I guarantee you I could have ended that war in 90 days without nuclear weapons.
But yet I would have done things that has been done in all other wars.
I would have killed people.
I would have destroyed supplies.
I would have made it demoralizing for the enemy.
And I'm talking about bombing their towns, their schools, their hospitals.
you know, flooding, breaking their dams and flooding out all their whole systems, their electricity, you know, all their hiding places, which are all underground.
There was a big dam in Hanoi, which just the water alone would have drowned everybody, you know.
It would have stopped.
Yeah, above ground, below ground, either one, you know.
But see, we didn't do that.
I mean, it's really, it's just really stupid.
And you sit there and you wonder,
You know, why?
You know, because all the movies you saw with John Wayne and Audie Murphy and all those guys, you know, it's like, you know, those are bad guys, you know, you go get them, and, you know, it's over.
